{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_oliver_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280600623/1930082401/0382.xml":{"full_text":"Special Articles\nPart 2\u2014B Pages\nEUROPEAN NATIONS SEEN\nGETTING READY FOR WAR\nProphecy for 1935 Based on French\nWeakness Due to Birthrate Lower Than\nItaly\u2019s and Greater War Losses.\nBT FRANK H. b.MONDS.\nTHE other day at the Willlams\ntown Conference a British pro\nfessor Indicated In words that\nstartled not a few of his hearers\nhis own view that Europe was\nSteadily and consistently preparing for\nB new war, which he explained was ex\npected somewhere between 1835 and\n1840. This statement, unfamiliar as it\nIs perhaps on our side of the water, has\nbeen a matter of common comment all\naver Europe.\nIn point of fact, the prophecy has\ngenerally been voiced in far more spe\ncific terms. \u201cA new war In 1835\u201d has\nbeen the usual version. In this shape\nthe forecast recalls the now forgotten\npre-war warning. Then the year of dis\naster was ordinarily set for 1816, with\nthe added phrase \u201cor when Russia com\npletes the reorganization of her army\nand the building of the strategic rail\nways on the German and Austrian\nfrontiers.\u201d\nToday the prophecy for 1835 Is based\ntoon several circumstances. In the\nfirst place, there has been a natural\nconsideration of the date fixed for the\nfinal evacuation of the occupied areas\nof the Rhineland. Obviously, Germany\nwould not recover her freedom of ac\ntion until this time. And all forecasts\nnaturally pay much attention to Ger\nmany. In so far as the new war might\nresult from a German decision to upset\nthe treaty of Versailles by violence and\nundertake to remake her eastern fron\ntiers by reconquering the Polish Cor\nridor and Upper Silesia, It has been\nplain that German action must wait\nupon the moment when French troops\nwere at last gone from German soil to\navoid making Germany the battle\nground, as France was In 1814-18.\nSecond Factor Reckoned.\nA second factor has similarly been\nreckoned In fixing the date at 1835.\nBeginning with 1815, the effect of the\nwar was enormously to lower the birth\nrate of all combatant countries, and the\nparticular victim was France, already\npossessing the lowest birthrate of all the\ngreat powers. Instead of 250,000 re\ncruits coming up for service, which Is\napproximately the annual French con\ntingent, the number of boys reaching\nthe age of 20 In 1825 will hardly exceed\n100,000 and for the next five years the\nnumbers will not Increase.\nDuring these five years, then, France\nwill be at her weakest. In the face of\nItaly her disadvantage will be most\nalarming, for Italy did not enter the\nwar until a year after France and her\nlosses were but half a million, against\n1,250,000 for France. Possessing a\nvastly higher birthrate, Italy will then\ncall to the colors in these critical years\nnot less than twice as many recruits as\nFrance, If she employs her full strength.\nAnd It is precisely between France and\nItaly that the danger of conflict has In\nrecent times seemed most acute.\nFrance, with her allies, notably Jugo\nslavia, where the war mortality was\nheaviest); Poland, which suffered almost\nequally; Rumania, which, like Serbia,\nwas long In the enemy's hand, win be\nat the low point exactly at the date\nwhen the possibility of a new conflict\nIs generally recognised. And Indeed It\nla this French weakness which has been\nthe basis for not a few of the alarming\nprophecies.\nThe danger is increased by the fact\nthat France has since the war reduced\nthe term of service for eonscrlpts from\nthree years to one, and no government\nwill dare now to impose twice aa long\na term of sendee, In view of the In\nevitable political consequences.\nIt Is this circumstance, too, which ex\nplains the opposition In France, such\nas there was. to the early evacuation\nof the Rhineland. Not a few French\nmot, backed by a considerable press,\nargued that France should stay in\nMainz until 1935, thus denying to Ger\nmany the opportunity to prepare In ad\nvance for a campaign In 1835. If the\nFrench troops did not retire until 1835,\nIt was urged, It would take Germany\nmost of the five dangerous years to\nprepare any new campaign.\nItaly Seems Dangerous Neighbor.\nBut the French troops have now\ngone, the Rhineland Is bare of allied\ngarrisons and, what Is most disturbing\nIn French quarters, the fortification of\nthe French frontiers has only Just begun\nand cannot be completed during the\nnext five years. Moreover, fortification\non the eastern frontier is bound to be\ndelayed by the present need to build\nvamnarfa nn tha Tfvalfnn hrmnrfprv\nramparts on tne luuan Dounaary. luopyrunt. i\u00bbw.i __\nAfter Blow From U. S. Prohibition\nt\nJERUSALEM. \u2014Palestine also suffers\nfrom prohibition regime in the United\nStates. Prior to the World War, virtu\nally the whole of the wine production\nwas exported to Russia and the United\nStates. Local consumption hardly\ncounted. Following upon the Bolshevik\nrevolution, however, America was al\nmost the only remaining market.\nThus the introduction of prohibition\nbrought about a serious crisis in the\nwine industry of the Holy Land. Vines\nwere uprooted and oranges planted in\ntheir stead. But the farmers who could\nnot hold out for six years until the new\nplantations began to yield were in a\nsorry plight. Only lately have condi\ntions started to improve.\nJewish Effect on Change.\nEven though the Palestine of the\ngble was renowned for its wine and\ne prophet pictured each inhabitant\nsitting under his own vinetree, viti\nculture had been practically non-exist\nent ever since the Jews were driven out\nof Palestine. A change came about\nwith the foundation of the first Jewish\ncolonies in the latter half of the last\ncentury. Before that, wine production\nhad in the main been confined to a few\nmonasteries for ritual purposes.\nIn the Jewish settlements, however,\nvineyards grew to such proportions that\nthe Jewish Farmers\u2019 Co-operate, with\nthe assistance of Baron Rothschild, es\ntablished in 1892, in Rishon-le-Zlon,\nsouth of Jaffa, and in Zichron Jacob,\nsouth of Haifa, some of the largest\nwine cellars of the world, second only\nto those of Bordeaux. The large im\nmigration of 1924-25 greatly Increased\nthe local consumption and largely made\nup for America\u2019s abstention.\nNs Longer Uprooted.\nVines are no longer uprooted. There\nIs no drunkenness to speak of in the\ncountry. Jews always have been known\nfor their moderation and the Moslems\nin the villages rigorously observe the\nrestrictions Imposed by their religion.\nIn the cities they no longer refuse a\nglass of light wine. Wines and liquors\nare so cheap that the poorest folk can\nafford them There are practically no\nsaloons in the Holy Land, and the wine\nshops serve merely as selling agencies.\nThe total consumption of wine, rum,\nbrandy and whisky does not exceed one\nliter per person per year. There are\nno breweries, although a type of barley\nsuited for brewing purposes grows near\n|fOaza. This is exported to Germany\nI t\nOn the whole, it Is an exaggeration\nto say that any considerable number of\nFrenchmen are today fearful of an\nearly German offensive. Italy and not\nGermany seems the dangerous neigh\nbor. but there remains the frightful\nquestion as to what action Germany\nmight take If France and Italy were at\nj war. Even If it did not take the form\nof a new march into France, German\nactivity might easily be directed toward\nthe reconstruction of the eastern fron\ntier at the expense of Poland.\nFrance Is, then, beyond all debate,\nmaking vast efforts to prepare her\nfrontiers against any possible menace\nwhich may arrive In 1835. And it Is\nperfectly true that these preparations\nare matched along the other side of the\nAlps. At the same time Jugoslavia,\nand Indeed all the succession States,\nincluding Poland, are apprehensive and\naccordingly active In organizing their\nmeans of defense.\nBriand's proposal for a discussion of\nthe project of a Uinted States of\nEurope patently falls In with this uni\nversal anxiety. It is fair to assume\nthat if all continental countries are\nconsidering combination or at least\nclose co-operation, the chances of war\nwill be materially lessened. But, on\nthe other hand, the fact that both the\nItalian and German answers to the\nFrench proposal have clearly hinted at\ntreaty revision and frontier amendment\nhas had disagreeable repercussions In\nParis.\nFew Really Disturbing Signs.\nIt Is a fact, as the British professor\nIndicated at Williams town, that Europe\nIs not merely nervous about 1835, but\nthat many European countries are tak\ning steps to Insure themselves against\npossible trouble. Italy apart, however,\nit Is hard to find at the moment any\nreally disturbing signs In the actions\nof any country. If Germany, Hungary,\nBulgaria and Lithuania unmistakably\nmean to obtain a revision of their\nfrontiers, none Is doing anything at the\nmoment which even remotely hints at\nmilitary activity.\nWe shall, unquestionably, hear much\nIn the next years of the possibility of\nwar In 1835. Moreover, since many\npeoples are resolved to change their\npresent status and those nations which\nare opposed to change will be weakest\nat this time, It is not difficult to build\nup a theoretical case In favor of a new\nconflict. Nor Is it hard to sustain such\na case by pointing to the obvious prep\narations for conflict going on along\nmany frontiers.\nFinally, it is true that, historically,\none may find precedent for Interest In\n1835. Fifteen years after Waterloo had\nabolished the Napoleonic Empire and\nenabled the allies of that time to re\nstore the Bourbons the July revolution\nIn Paris sent the last Bourbon packing\nand precipitated upheavals all over\nEurope which, without leading to any\nreal war, did begin the presses of re\nvision of the frontiers of the Congress\nof Vienna. i\nTwo Rated by Dictators.\nAside from France, however, all\nEuropean countries are at the moment\nplunged Into very grave economic\ncrises. Domestic difficulties, both po\nlitical and financial, dominate popular\nInterest. Italy and Soviet Russia are,\nit Is true, ruled by dictators and make\nno disguise of their hostility to existing\nconditions. Yet at bottom neither Italy\nnor Russia to in a position to make war\nand neither dictatorship, at heart,\nactually desires it, despite superficial\ndeclarations.\nAll in all, fixing the next war In Eu\nrope for 1835 seems, despite the appeal\ning arguments advanced, rather more\nthe product of fear than of actual\nsound reasoning. Europe to now, as It\nwas in 1814, at the mercy of an acci\ndent. The material out of which ware\nare made to plainly available on every\nhand, but with precious few exceptions\nall peoples still remain \"fed up\u201d in the\nmatter of conflict and every government\nIncluding the dictatorships, has sound\nreason for fearing the ultimate conse\nquences of leading Its supporters Into\nthe trenches.\nWar may come in 1835, Just as the\nend of the world may arrive, but today\nboth forecasts seem equally lacking in\nreal foundation. And If nations are\nmaking preparations against that date\nIt is not with the purpose to precipitate\nhostilities but to prevent them or, at the\nleast, to be fortified again them.\n(flfinvrlfht 1020.1\nand England for the production of ale.\nPalestine imports the beer It con\nsumes to the amount of approximately\n500,000 liters per year, being 200,000\nliters less than its wine consumption.\nBusiness Depression\nIs Felt by Temples\nThe business depression now prevail\ning throughout Japan affects not only\nbusiness but the temples. Three years\nago the Kwannon Temple, in Asakusa\nPark, Toklo, which draws the largest\nnumber of visitors and pilgrims of any\ntemple in the capital, averaged 8500 a\nday in small coin contributions. People\nwould go and throw pieces of money\ninto the wooden box in front of the\ntemple. Now, due to the slump, the in\ncome has dropped to the $125 level.\nThis state of affairs has necessitated a\ncomplete revision in the temple\u2019s bud\nget. Not only the Asakusa temple, but\npractically all the shrines, numbering\n112,000, and countless Buddhist temples\nas well as Christian churches in Japan,\nhave felt the sting of the business de\npression. In many cases temple priests\nhave been finding it extremely difficult\nto make both ends meet. The number\nof worshipers has not decreased, fig\nures prepared by the temples show, but\nmore now pay their devotions in hope\nof divine assistance in making money\nthan in finding a charitable way of\nspending it.\nFascists Take Over\nItalian Navy League\nThe Italian Navy League, which or\nganised pleasant lectures, cruises and\nentertainments for its members, was\nrecently taken over by the Fascist\nparty in celebration of the fact that\nthe Italian navy, six years hence, will\ncontain 402,000 tons of fighting ships,\ni A prominent Fascist, Achille fltarace,\ni has been appointed as its new presi\ndent. He took office with definite or\nders to \u201cpursue an intensive naval\npropaganda campaign\u2019\u2019\u2014a command\nhardly necessary since the government,\ns senators, deputies and general public\nr have lately accepted in full the na\nr tkmal propaganda for a more effective\nr navy.\n\nEDITORIAL. SECTION\n(She Jiundau Jitat\nWASHINGTON, D. C., SUNDAY MORNING, AUGUST 24, 1930.\nAmericas to Co-operate\nDelegates From 21 Republics to Stress Need of Co-operative Production and Guard for Food Supply\n\nr i K lll \u00df*i^*^Bf llll wn ni\u00df^iii m mmmmmtn mi I lir \"rnr-T n\nI v I''.*-\nTHE PAN-AMERICAN UNION BUILDING. JOSE COLOM (UPPER LEFT) AND LEON ESTABROOK (UPPER RIGHT).\nBY GRACE PHELPS.\nWHEN the delegates from the\n21 republics of North and\nSouth America gather In\nWashington on September 8\nfor the first bl-contlnental\nconference on agriculture ever con\nducted, they will plan to do for the\nfood supplies of the Western Hemis\nphere what the United States Depart\nment of Agriculture Is already doing\nfor this country. And, perhaps more\nsignificantly, what the British have\ndone for the entire British Empire\nand what the Dutch have done for\ntheir colonies.\nIn other words, they will survey the\nwhole field of crop production with a\nview to Immediate co-operation, scien\ntific production and conservation and\nwith an eye to the needs of future\ngenerations.\nGrouped Under Three Heads.\nAs originally planned, the program\nfpr the lnter-Amerlcan conference on\nagriculture, forestry and animal in\ndustry was grouped under three heads:\nFirst, problems dealing with research\nin agriculture and forestry develop\nEducation Aided by Radio\nSchool Subjects Stir Zeal to Learn\u2014lsolated Sections Particularly Profit\u2014Much Yet to Be Done\nBY GEORGE B. ZEHMER,\nDirector, Extension Department, Univeraitr\not Virginia.\nPRESIDENT GARFIELD\u2019S con\nception of a collage as a log\nwith Mark Hopkins on one end\nand a student on the other is\nfamiliar to every one concerned\nwith education. While this character\nization does not Include many things\nwhich today are regarded as essential,\nit reminds us of the two principal ele\nments in a teaching situation \u2014the\nteacher, fired with enthusiasm to in\nstruct, and the student, fired with zeal\nto learn. With the advent of radio, that\nnovel device which represents a com\nbination of human Imagination, scien\ntific achievement, technical skill and\nindustrial organization, carrying the\nhuman voice Into 11,000.000 American\nhomes, not to mention those in other\ncountries, the question of the educa\ntional value of this new and powerful\nlnstument is immediately raised. Will\nwhat is not called \u201cether\u201d take the\nplace of Mark\u2019s \"log\u201d in bringing to\ngether teacher and pupil?\nWhereas modern organisational meth\nods, with class rooms and lecture halls,\nhave made It possible for a single\nteacher to reach and Inspire larger\nnumbers than could possibly sit on the\nother end of the traditional log, the\nhuman voice over the radio may be\nimmediately conveyed into a universal,\nworld-wide institution, establishing per\nsonal relationships between the great\nest teachers of the world and a host\nof scattered, heretofore isolated, in\ndividuals.\nRadio Educational Agency.\nA may picture! Is it merely a fancy?\nImagination gone wild? At least many\nrecognised leaders in business, art, edu\ncation. politics and religious work hold\nhigh hopes of the educational contribu\ntions which this new agency will make\nto civilization.\nIn discussing the place of radio In\neducation it must be observed in the\nbeginning that the world \"education\u201d\nhas a popular as well as a specialised\nmeaning. Broadly interpreted, educa\nment and Improvement In methods and\npractices; second, problems of agricul\ntural economics, such as credits, trans\nportation and markets, and third, plant\nand animal diseases and pests, quaran\ntine and regulatory problems.\nSince there to now meeting In Sacra\nmento a Pan-American reciprocal con\nference which to Interested mainly In\nthe third topic, and since a similar\nconference for the discussion of com\nmercial problems will take place next\nyear in Washington, most of the topics\ndiscussed at this conference will be\nconcerned with production.\nAccording to agricultural specialists\nof both continents, there are two out\nstanding needs of tropical America:\nFirst, economic surveys of the agricul\ntural resources, and second, scientific\nproduction. Just how vital these needs\nare may be understood by the fact\nthat where once Central and South\nAmerica led the world In the produc\ntion of rubber, cacoa and quinine,\nmost of the world's rubber now comes\nfrom the Malay Peninsula, at least half\nthe supply of cacao comes from the\ngold coast and by far the most qui\nnine to grown In Java.\nThe cause of this change to scien\nm' m jJI Hk\nfarWDHI s/jy\ntion Includes anything which enlarges\nthe Intellectual horizon, adds to one\u2019s\nsum total of knowledge or Increases\n\u25a0kill In or appreciation of any worthy\nprocess or subject. In this sense, news\npapers, magazines and journals, travel,\nlibraries, museums and other enlight\nening agencies are educational. In the\nrestricted meaning of the term, educa\ntion signifies formalized instruction\nand professionalized processes with pur\nposeful and sustained effort. Usually\nclass room instruction within elemen\ntary or secondary schools or within col\nleges and universities, under trained\nteaphers, is implied.\nImportant Contributions Made.\nIf we consider education in the first\nsense, radio is unquestionably making\nImportant contributions. Its present\nvalue in organized class room instruc\ntion is problematical. But whatever its\npresent status may be, the ultimate ex\ntent and nature of its value in all\nforms of education are of great im\nportance and interest, first, because\nradio is so rapidly becoming an accepted\npart of every one\u2019s daily life; secondly,\nbecause the public desires the utilisa\ntion for its purposes of every Important\ndiscovery and invention.\nThat radio is being utilized today for\neducational purposes is evident when\nwe examine the programs broadcast\nfrom both educationally and privately\nowned stations. Fifteen-and-flve-tenths\nper cent of all broadcasting in this\noountry is of an educational nature.\nIn fact, so much educational material\nis on the air today that any one who\ndesires to do so frequently can get ln-\nA 4\ntific production, Instituted and fos\ntered by the British and Dutch.\nIn a statement by the late Dr. W.\nA. Orton, director of the Tropical Plant\nResearch Foundation of Washington,\nconcerning this problem he said:\n\u201cThe present movement of produc\ntion and export of tropical plant prod\nucts to away from Latin America and\ntoward the European colonies In the\nEast Indies, Asia and Africa where\nscientific support to being given to\nagriculture. The consumption of rub\nber has been multiplied many times,\nbut the center of production has moved\nto Oriental plantations.\n\u201cAmerican cacao producers are handi\ncapped by destructive diseases to which\nthey have not given sufficient research,\nwhereas the British government to\nmaintaining experiment stations to pro\nmote the culture of cacao In Africa.\nSimilarly, the Dutch have selected cer\ntain strains of the cinchona tree which\nto rich In quinine. In the same way\nforeign governments are giving marked\nattention to the support of the co\nlonial production of sugar, oils, cot\nton and other Important export crops,\nwith the result that the American pro\nduction to relatively at a standstill In\nstructlon or Information on the subject\nof Interest. Certainly if one uses some\ncare and ingenuity in selecting, he can\nget during the course of any week val\nuable instruction by radio on a large\nvariety of topics.\nNewspapers have co-operated heartily\nin announcing daily the most outstand\ning educational features. Yet there is\nneed for more systematic, general and\ncomplete announcements, perhaps, clas\nsified according to subject matter, of\nradio programs. Other countries are\nfar ahead of America in providing for\nthis service.\nExperiments In Progress.\nTo deny that many problems con\nnected with radio education are not\nwith us also would be futile; in fact,\nstupid. Many suggest themselves im\nmediately. What subjects can be taught\nbest by radio? If and when these are\ndetermined, can they be taught mere\neffectively by radio than by present\nmethods? What are good requirements\nfor educational broadcasting? How can\nan effective organization of educational\ninterests be had? How can educational\nbroadcasting be financed? A complete\nlist would be too long to Include here.\nThose lentloned are sufficient to em\nphasize the most Important need of the\nhour\u2014experimentation. Without care\nfully \u00bb.lected staffs with experien e and\nresearch ability and (not to be over\nlooked) resources, progress in educa\ntional broadcasting cannot go forwrrd\nas it should.\nSome Interesting experiments are now\nin program. The department of rural\neducation of teachers' college. Columbia\ncompanion with the World\u2019s consump\ntion of their tropical products.\u201d\nAt the same time he draws this pic\nture of conditions Dr. Orton pointed\nout that the products of tropical coun\ntries are indispensable to the world.\nThere will be more of the great staples,\nsuch as rubber, coffee and sugar, need\ned every year, and uses will be found\nfor many minor and as yet unde\nveloped tropical products.\nIt Is hoped that the conference will\nestablish a permanent pan-American\norganization for scientific agricultural\nresearch, with experiment stations\nwhich will serve all Latin American\ncountries and at the same time train\nmen in tropical agriculture. A start\nin this direction already has been made\nby the establishment of a division of\nagricultural co-operation by the Pen-\nAmerioan Union after its sixth confer\nence in Havana, in 1928. This division\nis chiefly a correspondence bureau, but,\naccording to its director, Dr. Jose Go\nlem, the letters that come in from\nevery country iar Central and South\nAmerica show how great the need is\nfor scientific organisation.\nLeon Estabrook, assistant director of\n(Continued on Fourth Page.)\nUniversity, Is co-operating with the\nKeith Fund in an effort to discover the\nvalue of radio in rurrl schools. About\n100 schools of various rural types are\nInvolved. They extend from Virginia\nup Into New England and as far west as\nthe Alleghenies. The supervisor of the\nproject reports that in spite of many\napparent difficulties, which fortunately\ncan be overcome to some extent, radio\noffers to rural schools some distinct\nadvantages which they could not obtain\nthrough any other medium. Eight ad\nvantages are pointed out.\nA more extensive experiment Is the\nOhio School of the /ir. It* parjjose is\nto help determine the part which radio\ncan play effectively in organised class\nroom instruction, especially in public\nelementary and secondary schools. Its\ni specific aim is to teach pupils over the\nI air the things they need to k iow that\ncan be most effectively taught in that\nway. This school is a division of the\nOhio State Department of Education,\nwhich is one of the few government\nowned and operated stations in America.\nThe work is offered as a supplement\nto that given in the class room and not\nas a substitute for it. The conclusions\ndrawn from this experiment, which\ndoubtless will extend over several years,\nshould prove of much value to educa\ntional Interests.\nA third experiment is being conducted\nto help determine the value of radio\neducationally In homes of illiterates or\nnear Illiterates. Receiving sets have\nbeen Installed in selected mountain\nhomes in Virginia near President Hoo\nver\u2019s Summer camp. The extension\ndepartment and School of Sociology of\nthe University of Virginia is conducting\nthis investigation. Work of installing\nreceivers and of checking results only\nrecently was begun, and no limits of\ntime have been determined.\nPerhaps other studies of equal inter\nest and importance are in progress. The\nnext few years should see many more\nunder way.\nA second Important need is better or\nran Isation and leadership among edu\n(Contjjpued on Fourth Page.)\nEditorial Page\nWETS HOPE TO RREAK DRY\nMORALE BY SENATE GAINS\nNumerical Computations Reveal Literary\nDigest Poll Not True Forecast on\nNext Congress.\nBT MARK SULLIVAN.\nWITH tbe party primaries of\nthis political year more than\nhalf behind us It is possible\ntoestlmate the results so far,\nas respects wet versus dry.\nThe estimate in its bearing upon the\nwet versus dry fight and in its bearing\nupon the wetness or dryness of the\nnext Congress, can only be partial, for\nthe most Important of the States as\nrespects this question are yet to hold\ntheir primaries or conventions. Massa\nchusetts and New York both hold pri\nmaries September IS and New York\nhas a State convention a little later.\nIn both these States are situations\nwhich, as they come to a head, will de\ntermine whether the Republican party\nin these States 1s to be wet. (The\nDemocratic party in these two States\nis already wet.)\nWest Not Over Knthuslastie.\nAs respects the primaries already\nheld, the wets have made some con\ncrete gains\u2014yet not enough, so far, to\nbe more than minor movements in a\nconflict that has already been under\nway 10 years since the prohibition\namendment went into effect and can\nnot possibly come to a conclusion for\nseveral years more.\nThough the gains of the wets are\ndefinite and unmistakable, the state of\nmind of the wet leaders is far short of\nimmediate confidence. They are less\nconfident\u2014with respect to making 1930\na turning-point year\u2014than they were\na few months ago. At one time,\nshortly after the Literary Digest poll\nshowed (apparently) only six States\nnow dry in sentiment, some of the wet\nleaders expected that the Congress to\nbe elected in November would be wet.\nThat was a grotesque hope for them at\nthe time they entertained it and they\nhave now abandoned It\nDigest Poll Not Accurate Index.\nThe Literary Digest poll was correct,\nin the sense that it was taken accu\nrately and conscientiously\u2014but clearly\nit was not correct as an index to wet\nversus dry political sentiment in the\nStates. In the final Digest poll every\nState except six showed a majority\nagainst prohibition; that is, a majority\nmade up of those favoring repeal added\nto those favoring modification. To\nstate it another way, only six States\nshowed a majority for continuance of\nthe eighteenth amendment and strict\nenforcement of it\u2014the six States being\nArkansas, Kansas, North Carolina, Mis\nsissippi, Oklahoma and Tennessee.\nIn a broad way the Digest poll was\nfaithful to the general trend. That is,\nthe States that went dry in the Digest\npoll were the States well known to be\nstrongly dry, as in the list above. And.\nthe States that went strongly wet in\nthe Digest poll were the ones known by\nother evidence to be strongly wet.\nBut It was and is clear that the Di\ngest poll on prohibition was not ac\ncurate in the sense that previous polls\ntaken by the same periodical about\nPresidential elections were remarkably\naccurate. If the Digest poll were ac\ncurate in the sense of being a correct\nindex of tile political attitude on pro\nhibition\u2014if the Digest poll were ac\ncurate in that sense (as many wets at\nthe time thought it was) then the S*T\nate and House to be elected in Novem\nber would be more than five-sixths wet\nas respects the House and fully two\nthirds wet as respects the Senate. And\nthe fact is nothing even faintly ap\nproaching that, hardly even a step to\nward that, is going to take place. If\nthe Digest poll were an accurate index\nin the political sense, the prohibition\namendment could be repealed within\ntwo years\u2014and the hard political fact\nis that no measurable progress has been\nmade toward repeal of the prohibition\namendment.\nFell Raised Wet Hopes Tee High.\nAt the time of the Literary Digest poll\ngreat masses of wets, and even some\nwet leaders, believed they could win\nthis November and in the Congress to\nbe elected this November, a victory cor\nresponding to the Digest poll\u2014that is,\nrepeal of the prohibition amendment,\nor modification of It\nAt the present time, however, the\nnow existing state of mind of wet\nleaders who are well-informed is sug\ngested by one who expresses the maxi\nmum wet hope for November in the\nfollowing words: \"This November will\nbe only a skirmish but we wets will\nmake enough gains to have a bad effect\non dry morale and the impression of\nrecession of prohibition will be inten\nsified.\"\nThis is a reasonable state of mind,\nand the facts of this year\u2019s primaries\nJustify it. The truth, as respects the\nprohibition fight in this campaign of\n1930 is that the wets have made some\nconcrete gains\u2014and yet not such gains\nas need give confident hope to the wets,\nor dismay the drys.\nWet Advances Impressive, However.\nNevertheless the wet advances are\nImpressive. The most important is the\none that occurred in New Jersey. It is\nmot merely that a wet, Ambassador\nMorrow, won the Republican nomina\ntion for Senator from one of the coun\ntry\u2019s outstanding drys, Representative\nFort. The impressive advantages from\nthe wet point of view of their New\nJersey victory are two: First, they have\npractically secured the presence, in the\nSenate, in the person of Mr. Morrow, of\na man of the very highest character\nwho is a wet. Mr. Morrow\u2019s known\nelevation of mind and character, his\nall-round eminence, are such that even\ndrys have confidence in him. If the\nend of this wet versus dry fight in the\nNation is to be some kind of compro\nmise and adjustment, and if Mr. Mor\nrow remains in the Senate long enough,\nhe will have a leading part in whatever\nis to be the final status.\nThe second advantage to the wets in\nthe New Jersey outcome is that the\nRepublican party in that State, having\nformerly been dry, is now formally wet.\nThat step of the Repablican party in\nNew Jersey to a formal wet position is\nprobably the largest single battle the\nwets have won in the Nation since the\nfight began. If it should now turn out,\nas a result of the September primaries\nin New and Massachusetts, that\nthe Republican party in those two\nStates should go wet also\u2014in that event\nthe wets would be entrenched, in both\nparties, in a solid stronghold contain\ning a measurable percentage of the\nvoting strength and the political power\nof the country.\nOkie Victory Ceospkaoaa.\nNext to the nomination of a Repub\nlican wet in New Jersey and the Re\npublican organization in that State go\ning formally wet, the other conspicuous\nvictory of the wets was the winning of\nthe Democratic Senatorial primary in\nOhio. Ohio is the birthplace and home\nof the Anti-Saloon League. Ohio also\nhas been, slnoe the Civil War, a State\ndecisive in national political sentiment,\nrecognized as such, and deferred to as\nsuch by leaders of both political parties.\nAs Ohio goes, so go those politicians\nwho keep their ears to the ground.\nOhio is a true political barometer\u2014and\nOhio has been dry.\nThat a considerable portion of the\nDemocratic party in Ohio has been wet\nhas always been well known. What\nthe Democrats did, however, at the Sen*\natortal primary on the 12th of this\nmonth, constituted a longer step to\nward wetness than any one event that\nhas occurred in Ohio since 1920. The\nDemocratic wets searched out and\nfound in Ohio, as the Republican wets\nfound in New Jersey, a man of the\nhighest character and standing, a Cleve\nland lawyer named Robert J. Bulkley.\nThey entered him in the primaries for\nthe Senatorial nomination. This one\nwet ran against a field that Included\nfour drys. One wet running against\nfour drys had, of course, a tactical ad\nvantage. But the fact is, nobody except\nthe shrewdest observers expected Bulk\nley to win. His winning, by a vote\npractically twice that of his nearest\ndry competitor, was a conspicuous sign\nof the strength of wet sentiment among\nthe Ohio Democrats.\nAs things stand now, the Democrats\nin Ohio have a wet candidate for Sen\nator whose strength is by no means\nconfined to his wetness. Mr. Bulkley'\u25a0\nability and stand are such that his\npresence in the Senate would be an ele\nvation of that body. Such a man, ob\nviously. has a good chance of winnings\nwhether he be wet or dry. And If th*\nDemocrats win the Ohio senatorial elec\ntion, the strength of the wets in th*\nSenate will be increased, not only by\none Senator numerically, but by a man\nwith gifts that can win him widespread\nnubile confidence.\nMorrow Gain Not Numerical.\nIf one surveys all the possible wet\ngains in the next Senate they make an\nimpressive showing. So far they aro\nonly \"possible\" gains. All that one can\nsay is that in several States, and in\nboth parties, wets have been nominated\nas candidates for Senator who have a\nstrong chance of winning.\nThe most conspicuous is Morrow o<\nNew Jersey. Morrow, it is true, would\nnot be a net gain to the wets in a nu\nmerical sense, since it will be nothing\nnew for New Jersey to elect a wet Sen\nator. Next, in Ohio, the Democrat*\nhave nominated a man who is at one*\nwet and very able and who if he should\nbe elected in November, will be a neb\ngain of one to the wets.\nIn Oklahoma the Democrats hava\nnominated a wet. Oklahoma is a\ndoubtful State, and if the wet Demo\ncratic candidate should win, he would\nbe a net gain to tbe wets in the Senate.\nIn Montana the Republicans hava\nnominated a wet to run against the\ndry Democrat, Senator Thomas F.\nWalsh. Montana is clearly a doubtful\nState (as between Republicans and\nDemocrats), anddf the wet Republican\ncandidate should defeat Senator Walsh\nthat again would be a net gain of one\nin the Senate. (Further than this, tha\ndefeat of a conspicuous dry Democrat,\nsuch as Senator Walsh of Montana,\nwould have moral effect outside tha\nState and would accelerate the present\ntendency of the Democratic party na\ntionally to go wet).\nIn Nebraska, as in Ohio, the Demo\ncrats have nominated a candidate for\nSenator who is at ones able and ex\nperienced, ex-Sanator Gilbert M. Hitch*\ncock. If wet Democratic Candidate\nHitchcock should defeat dry Repub\nlican (Republican nominally) Senator\nNorris, here again would be a net wet\ngain of one in the Senate.\nAgainst these possible net gains for\nthe wets In the Senate there are no\ncorresponding dry gains. There is no\nBtate as to which a Senate seat now\nheld by a wet ie apt to be displaced by\na dry.\nWet# Might Gaia 8 Votes.\nIf we assume that in all the Sena\ntorial elections mentioned above tha\nwet candidate should win, and if tho\nwets get similar advantages in primaries\nyet to be held\u2014in that event the net\naddition to wet strength in the Senate\nwould be about five.\nIf we translate this into numerical\nfigures in tbe Benate, it doesn\u2019t go very\nfar. The Senate consists of 96 men.\nIf we try to separate them into wets\nand drys, there is a margin of 5 or g\nthat cannot be classified positively\neither way. Omitting this half dozen\nor so, it is very close to accurate to\nsay that in the Senate as now con\nstituted there are about 70 drys and\nabout 20 wets. Assume that the wets\nmake all the gains of Senate seats\nthey can possibly gain in the coming\nNovember elections, and there will still\nbe 06 drys to 25 wets.\nTo make a gain of five seats at each\nelection, in a series of elections that\noccur only once every two years\u2014tiiat\nis a snaiMs-gait progress for the wets.\nAt that rate it would take the wets\n20 years, assuming they should never\nhave a setback, to control two-thirds\nof the Senate\u2014which they must con\ntrol before they can take even the first\nstep in repealing the eighteenth\namendment.\nIf you say this to the wet leaders\nthey reply that It won\u2019t work out that\nway. It Is not their expectation tc\nmake their gains one Senator at a.\ntime, or five Senators at a time. Their\ntheory and their plan is that wet sen\ntiment shall make sporadic gains, elec\ntion by election, for a few years; that\nafter this has gone on for some tlma\npoliticians everywhere will take notice,\nand that then there will be a general\noverturn.\nThere is much soundness in this\ntheory of strategy. Assuming the\nsoundness of the tactics, the wets are\nmaking in this year\u2019s primaries th*\nsort of sporadic gains that ars likely,\nto Impress politicians.\nPermanent Speedway\nPlanned in South Africa\nThe experience of Kaye Don, the\nBritish racing motorist, on Daytona\nBeach has revived the scheme in South\nAfrica for a permanent speedway at\nVemeuk Pan, where Capt Malcolm\nCampbell last year covered a mile aV\nslightly over 218 miles an hour, after\nhaving come here to beat Lockhart\u2019s\nrecord of 207 miles an hour. Slnee\nthen the elements have been kind t\u00bb\nthe track constructed for Oapt. Camp\nbell and a few days' work would put 12\nmiles of it in good trim. But there must-'\nbe few who would go to Vemeuk Pan\neven in quest of a record. An ugly, sun\nscorched, dried-up lake, it is a laud of\nsnakes and scorpions, but not of\nhumans.\nSees Lure of the Land\nDominating Canada\nThe lure of the land is evidently still\ndominant if the demand for Canadian\ngovernment homestead lands in West\nern Canada may be taken as a criterion.\nLast year about 2,775,000 acres were\ntaken up by settlers, an Increase of\n288.000 acres over 1028. The total\nnumber of entries in 1920 for 180 acre*\nof homestead lands offered free to set\ntlers on payment of a registration fee\nof $lO was 17,145, an increase of I,TT\u00bb\nentries over tha year before, J","height":"25215","width":"19659"}}
